    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix buffer overread in PNF PHY REL12 parameter unpacking\n\n### Summary\nThe nfapi P5 interface unpacking function for PNF PHY REL12 parameters contained an incorrect element size calculation that could lead to buffer overreads when processing configuration messages. The issue occurred in `unpack_pnf_phy_rel12_value()` where `sizeof(nfapi_pnf_phy_rel12_t)` was used instead of `sizeof(nfapi_pnf_phy_rel12_info_t)` for array element sizing.\n\nThis fix corrects the element size parameter and fixes an incorrectly named unpack function that was causing mismatches in function pointer references.\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/nfapi/src/nfapi_p5.c`: Fixed element size in `unpack_pnf_phy_rel12_value()` and corrected function naming for `unpack_pnf_phy_rel12_info()`.\n\n### Reproduction\nWhen the VNF sends a PNF_PARAM_RESPONSE message containing PNF PHY REL12 configuration TLVs, the incorrect element size causes the unpacking logic to read beyond the allocated buffer boundaries. This can be observed as memory corruption or segmentation faults during message processing, particularly when the message contains multiple PHY configurations.\n\nThe issue is triggered when:\n1. A PNF_PARAM_RESPONSE message is received with PNF_PHY_REL12_TAG TLV\n2. The message contains more than one PHY configuration entry\n3. The unpacking function attempts to process the array with incorrect sizing\n\nSymptoms include unexpected crashes during P5 message handling or corrupted configuration data being processed by the PHY layer.\n"
}